# loomcycle SECRETS — copy to .env.local and fill in.
#
# This file holds ONLY secret-bearing values: provider API keys, the
# sidecar bearer, the WebSearch key, and the secret VALUES behind any
# trigger-credential env names you allowlist in .env.insecure. Keep it
# out of version control — `.gitignore` ignores `.env.local`; only this
# `.example` template is committed.
#
# Companion file: .env.insecure (non-secret operational config — listen
# addr, sandbox roots, feature flags, allowlists). See
# `.env.insecure.example` and docs/CONFIGURATION.md §9c for the split's
# rationale. Both files are sourced at startup by loomcycle.sh /
# loomcycle-mcp.sh.

# ─── Provider keys (only the ones you'll use need to be set) ──────────
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
OPENAI_API_KEY=
# DEEPSEEK_API_KEY=
# GEMINI_API_KEY=

# Hosted ollama.com (the `ollama` provider) authenticates with a Bearer
# token. The local-network `ollama-local` provider needs NO key — it is
# driven by OLLAMA_BASE_URL in .env.insecure.
# OLLAMA_API_KEY=

# ─── Sidecar bearer ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Bearer token /v1 routes require. Empty = dev-mode unauthenticated;
# loomcycle prints a WARNING at startup so this is hard to forget.
# In a multi-tenant deployment this becomes the admin token (RFC L) —
# see docs/CONFIGURATION.md §9b.
LOOMCYCLE_AUTH_TOKEN=

# ─── Tenant credentials master key (RFC AR) ───────────────────────────
# Enables the CredentialDef inline backend — per-tenant / per-user encrypted
# API secrets referenced elsewhere as $cred:<name>. 32 bytes, base64:
#   LOOMCYCLE_SECRET_KEY=$(openssl rand -base64 32)
# Unset → inline credentials are disabled (fail-closed, never plaintext).
# Set _PREVIOUS to the prior key during a rotation grace window. See
# docs/CREDENTIALS.md.
# LOOMCYCLE_SECRET_KEY=
# LOOMCYCLE_SECRET_KEY_PREVIOUS=

# ─── WebSearch ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Brave Search API key. 2k/month free tier.
# BRAVE_API_KEY=

# ─── Trigger-credential secret VALUES ─────────────────────────────────
# A webhook's signing_secret_env / bearer_token_env, and any scheduler /
# webhook user_credentials_from_env, name an env VAR; the secret VALUE
# behind that name lives HERE. The NAME is authorized in .env.insecure
# (LOOMCYCLE_WEBHOOKS_ENV_ALLOWLIST / LOOMCYCLE_SCHEDULER_ENV_ALLOWLIST),
# or auto-allowed for verify secrets when LOOMCYCLE_*-prefixed.
#
# Examples (match the names you reference from your webhooks/schedules):
# LOOMCYCLE_GITEA_WEBHOOK_SECRET=     # HMAC verify secret (LOOMCYCLE_* ⇒ auto-allowed)
# GITEA_WEBHOOK_SECRET=               # non-prefixed ⇒ must be allowlisted / static-declared
# STRIPE_WH_SECRET=
# GITEA_API_TOKEN=                    # injected credential reachable by the agent's tools

# ─── Declared-principal bearer secrets (RFC AO) ───────────────────────
# A `principals:` block in loomcycle.yaml declares a static (tenant, user)
# login and names the env var holding its bearer via `token_env:`. The
# SECRET VALUE behind that name lives HERE (the yaml carries only the name).
# Use the SAME token for the Web UI login and an MCP thin client
# (LOOMCYCLE_MCP_UPSTREAM_TOKEN) so both resolve to the same (tenant,
# subject) — see docs/CONFIGURATION.md "Declared principals".
# LOOMCYCLE_TOKEN_MARKETING=          # bearer for principals.marketing
# LOOMCYCLE_TOKEN_OPS=                # bearer for principals.ops-admin
